blocks.value: Impact of Lifestyle Intervention for Patients with Prostate Cancer

A ndrogen-deprivation therapy (ADT) is the mainstay of treatment for advanced or metastatic prostate cancer (PCa). 1 In general, the adverse effects of continuous ADT increase over the duration of treatment, and its long-term use may lead to obesity, insulin resistance, fatigue, cardiovascular disease, reduced lean mass, osteoporosis, and psychological morbidity. 2 Depression, dementia, and anxiety are the most common psychological morbidities that exacerbate reduced quality-of-life (QoL), and they have been reported to develop in up to 28% of men treated with longterm ADT. 3,4 Moreover, the magnitude of psychological distress has been reported to increase over the first year of ADT, with a 4-fold greater risk of suicide compared to controls. 5,6 To reduce the detrimental effects of psychological morbidity on QoL in PCa patients, evidence-based recommendations support that implementation of an exercise regimen, patient intervention with

education packages, and clinician-led patient support groups. Indeed, exercise regimens have been shown to alleviate several adverse effects of ADT, such as cardiovascular disease, fatigue, metabolic syndrome, depression, and osteoporosis. Although the majority of physicians believe in the beneficial effect of exercise to improve QoL, the results of a European Web-based survey showed that only one-third of the respondents promoted exercise treatment due to the lack of time and low availability of supervised programs. Moreover, the distribution of educational materials alone, in the absence of other interventions, has been insufficient to motivate the patient to initiate or increase physical activity (PA). A supervised exercise program should be individually tailored to meet the patient's needs according to their diagnosis, comorbidity, and their general fitness and safety. A self-report questionnaire is the most commonly used tool to assess physical activity when counseling patients. Bourke et al reported results from a randomized trial that investigated the effect of lifestyle modification program on the QoL of patients with PCa receiving ADT. In that study, positive results were reported based on self-report questionnaires. However, self-reporting methods are known to underestimate the time spent in sedentary behavior (SB) and overestimate the time and degree of physical activity (PA). Therefore, objective measurements using accelerometry are warranted to provide reliable estimates of PA and SB, and to provide tailored exercise supervision.
Current evidence supports the use of exercise interventions to improve QoL in men with PCa receiving ADT. However, there is little evidence to support which combination of supportive measures would result in a clinically meaningful improvement in QoL. In this study, we report the results of a randomized-controlled trial designed to assess the efficacy of a structured lifestyle modification program for improving and sustaining QoL in men on long-term ADT.

Patients with advanced PCa on long-term ADT were recruited prospectively from Gangnam Severance Hospital in South Korea between Febru-ary 2018 and May 2019. All patients of a single consultant (K.C.K.) were offered to participate in this study after receiving a detailed explanation of the design and goals of the study. Participants were randomized at a 1:1 ratio according to a computergenerated random patient number list (Figure). Patients with recent angina, myocardial infarction, uncontrolled hypertension, and Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) performance status ≥ 2 were excluded (N = 9). ECOG performance status is a measurement tool that describes a patient's level of functioning in terms of their ability to care for themselves, daily activity, and physical ability. Patients with ECOG performance status ≥ 2 were excluded from recruitment because they were considered unable to carryout the structured lifestyle intervention.
After baseline screening, the trial involved 2 supervision visits (week 4 and week 8) and one maintenance visit (week 12). At each visit, self-reports and accelerometers were used to assess PA and SB, and questionnaires were used to measure QoL, life satisfaction, anxiety, and depression.

The intervention arm received structured lifestyle intervention in the form of education to promote both light PA and moderate-to-vigorous physical activity (MVPA), as well as to reduce SB. Patient education was performed by sports medicine specialists (S.P. and K.K.) during each of 2 supervision visits. In addition, we distributed educational materials, including PA guidelines for Koreans, a diary in which the patients could record their PA, and motivational text messages to the patients.
The Korean PA guidelines, published by the Ministry of Health and Welfare of South Korea, include information on the definition and types of PA that are best suited for the promotion of PA in older adults. Entries in the self-reported PA diary were used to confirm whether the participants successfully managed to engage in PA (≥ 150 minutes/ week of moderate PA 3 times per week). To motivate patients to engage in PA, the PA diary included information on the importance of engaging in PA in everyday life, as well as the types of exercises that correspond with each PA intensity. Motivational text messages were developed to promote and maintain PA, and were sent 3 times per week (Table).
Participants in the control arm were given only the PA guidelines, and no restrictions were placed on their exercise behaviors over the study period.

The patients' QoL was assessed using the Korean version of the European Organization for Research and Treatment of Cancer (EORTC) Quality of Life Questionnaire-30 (QLQ-C30) Version 3. The World Health Organization defines QoL as "an individual's perception of his or her position in life, in the context of the culture and value systems in which they live and in relation to their goals, expectations, standards, and concerns." Participants were required to answer 30 questions (functional scale = 15: physical, role, cognitive, emotional, and social; Cronbach alpha = 0.940; symptom scale = 13: fatigue, pain, and nausea/vomiting, dyspnea, sleep, appetite loss, constipation, diarrhea, and financial difficulties; global health = 2; α = 0.861) using 4-(1 = 'not at all' to 4 = 'very much') or 7-point (1 = 'very bad' to 7 = 'very good') Likert scales.
Life satisfaction was assessed using the Korean version of the Satisfaction with Life Scale (SWLS). Life satisfaction was defined as how people perceived the magnitude of positive values and beliefs about their choices. The scale had 5 items and a 7-point Likert scale (1 = 'strongly disagree' to 7 = 'strongly agree').
Anxiety and depression were assessed using the Korean version of the Hospital Anxiety Disorder Scale (HADS). The scale has 7 items for anxiety ("I get sudden feelings of panic"; 0 = 'not at all' to 3 = 'very much'; α = 0.877) and 7 items for depression

("I feel as if I am slowed down"; 0 = 'not at all' to 3 = 'nearly always; α = 0.815).
Self-reported PA and SB were assessed by the Korean version of the International Physical Activity Questionnaire (IPAQ). Participants were asked to record the time they spent engaging in light (eg, walking) and moderate (eg, carrying light loads, bicycling)-to-vigorous PA (eg, heavy lifting, aerobics, fast bicycling) over the past week. Time spent engaged in light PA and MVPA were divided in a weekly basis for the analyses. Daily time spent sitting was assessed using separate questionnaire items.
Device-measured PA and SB were assessed by using a waist-worn accelerometer (Model: GT3X; Actigraph, Pensacola, FL) for one week. Data were considered valid when the accelerometer was worn for at least one day (at least 600 minutes/day) at a 60-second epoch. Each period of activity was categorized as MVPA (≥ 2020 counts/minute), light ▪ Try walking over a short distance. Sample size for the mixed model (repeated measures ANOVA) was calculated using G*Power 3.1.9.2 (Program written, conceived, and designed by Franz, University of Kiel, Germany). In con-

Patient demographics were compared between groups using descriptive statistics. Group comparisons were assessed by independent t-tests for analysis of continuous variables, and by the chi-square test for analysis of 2 or more variables. Linear mixed models were used to assess changes in QoL, life satisfaction, anxiety, depression, self-reported and device-measured light PA and MVPA, and SB between intervention and control arms. Linear mixed models were used to account for missing data points; therefore, all participants were included in the analyses. A series of linear mixed models for each outcome variable were performed using a model with unstructured variance and a compound symmetry, including the random intercept. Time (within), group (between), and time x group were included to investigate whether changes overtime were different between groups. Statistical significance was set at .05, and all analyses were conducted using IBM SPSS ® Statistics (IBM Corporation, Chicago, IL).

Overall, 21 participants were randomized to either intervention (N = 11) or control arm (N = 10). Baseline evaluation demonstrated no significant differences between the arms in terms of patients' age, clinicopathological features related to PCa, body mass index, or performance status (Table).

Statistically significant improvements in QoL were reported during the study period (p < .01; Table). The beneficial change in QoL reported in the intervention arm (M 1 = 9.09, M 4 = 9.63) was significantly greater than that of the control arm (M 1 = 8.90, M 4 = 8.00; p < .01). Notably, improvements in QoL were sustained at the maintenance time-point.
No significant changes in life satisfaction or anxiety were reported (p = .134 and p = .278, respectively) during the study period. There were no significant differences in changes of life satisfaction (p = .098) and anxiety (p = .071) between the intervention and control arms. Significant improvements in depression were reported during the study period (p < .01). The beneficial change in depression reported in intervention arm (M 1 = 7.73, M 4 = 5.63) was significantly greater than that of control arm (M 1 = 9.80, M 4 = 11.00; p < .01). Notably, improvements in depression were sustained at the maintenance time-point.

Overall, there were no statistically significant improvements in self-reported MVPA (p = .169; Table), although the intervention arm showed Despite improvements in self-reported outcomes, there were no statistically significant changes in device-measured MVPA outcomes (p = .247). Although a significant difference in device- measured light PA was measured (p = .001), there were no statistically significant differences in the changes between intervention (M 1 = 31.03, M 4 = 19.89) and control arms (M 1 = 31.84, M 4 = 26.31; p = .081). Likewise, device-measured SB outcomes were significantly improved (p = .004); however, there were no statistically significant differences in the changes between the intervention arm (M 1 = 64.35, M 4 = 77.79) and the control arm (M 1 = 63.44, M 4 = 71.98; p = .250). In all participants, no harmful events were observed during the study period.

A physically active lifestyle is key to maintaining good mental health and QoL in older adults. According to a previous study using accelerometers to assess activity, men over 60 years of age were found to spend 71% of the day engaged in SB. Exercise among the older men was mostly low-intensity PA, and only one percent of the day was devoted to MVPA. A sedentary lifestyle is negatively associated with QoL and depression in older adults. Given that the rate of depression in American men receiving ADT is 8-fold greater than in the general male population and 32-fold greater than in men over 65 years of age, it is important to offer lifestyle modification programs to patients on long-term ADT. The strength of our structured lifestyle intervention program was the multimodal approach we implemented to maximize the frequency and intensity of PA and to reduce SB. First, at enrollment, patients were provided education to promote both light PA and MVPA, as well as to reduce SB by a team of sports science specialists. This education included encouragement to engage in exercise programs tailored to the individual patient based on their subjective physical and mental health questionnaire responses, and assessment of objective accelerometer-monitored SB and PA during the preceding 4 weeks. For instance, patients with axial bone metastases who had been engaging in vigorous PA were given recommendations to engage in light-to-moderate PA, reduce SB, and refrain from weight-bearing exercise. Second, educational material regarding the importance of exercise for physical and mental health in patients with PCa was produced and distributed to patients in the intervention arm of this study. The vast majority of men with advanced PCa on ADT did not meet the general recommendations for exercise intensity and frequency. Therefore, an educational package containing information on the adverse effects of ADT and how exercise can alleviate such symptoms were distributed. Third, to maximize exercise motivation, text messages with information on the importance of exercise were sent every 2 days during intervention. The text messages were developed based on a self-determination motivational theory. It has been suggested that support of patient autonomy, such as providing adequate information and encouragement/support from health professionals, can help motivate and maintain human behavior. Our structured lifestyle intervention program improved QoL and reduced depression in men with PCa on long-term ADT, and its beneficial effects were maintained after withdrawal of intervention. Depression and anxiety are the most common psychological morbidities experienced by cancer survivors. For patients with PCa, such conditions maybe aggravated by long-term ADT, resulting in poorer treatment outcomes, increased hospital stays, and higher mortality rates. Exercise promotes positive metabolic effects by triggering anabolism and stimulating physiological changes in multiorgan systems. In patients with PCa, early exercise intervention has been shown to improve QoL components, including psychological distress. However, due to the uncertain outcomes of interventional studies resulting from the absence of an evidence-based recommendation for exercise intervention, until recently, supervised exercise programs were not acknowledged as routine management for patients on ADT. Our lifestyle intervention program was developed based on the hypothesis that a physician-driven recommendation may trigger the decision-making process to start and maintain an exercise program and ultimately improve mental health-related outcomes. We believe the key to our positive results can be attributed to our use of physician-driven multimodal interventions, including individually tailored exercise feedback based on self-reported diary, accelerometer-monitored measurements, and text messaging.
A noteworthy observation of our study was that the intervention failed to improve the frequency or intensity of device-measured PA parameters, but improved QoL was nonetheless reported among study participants. There maybe several explanations for this finding. A substantial proportion of our participants had axial bone metastases, and they refrained from vigorous PA and weight-bearing exercise. The maintenance of PA to a light-tomoderate degree in these patients may have affected comparative accelerometer-based parameters between the study groups. Moreover, 33% of the participants had ECOG performance status of greater than one, which may have served as a hindrance to a significant increase in moderate-to-vigorous PA.
Our study had several limitations. First, the small number of participants and PA data using accelerometers may have limited meaningful analyses, and the results might be different with a larger number of participants. In addition, patients were enrolled from a single center, which may not justify the generalizability of our results. Second, all participants had a stable disease status over the study period. The beneficial effect of the lifestyle intervention program reported in our study participants may not apply to patients with progressive or debilitating disease. Third, a longer interval to maintenance visit is warranted to confirm the effect of our intervention program on long-term QoL. Fourth, the results from self-reported PA and SB may have underestimated the time spent in SB and overestimated the time and degree of PA. Nevertheless, we believe that this effect is inherent in any self-reported results, which led us to use objective accelerometry measurements. Lastly, the cost-effectiveness of such interventions should be investigated to determine their place in routine care. Nevertheless, our results add evidence to the literature indicating that physician-driven intervention in any form has the potential to improve psychological health in patients receiving ADT.
A physician-driven, structured lifestyle intervention program should be offered, whenever indicated, to patients on ADT due to its inherent advantage related to reducing anxiety and depression. Further research is warranted to investigate the therapeutic contents and concepts for an optimal intervention program for these patients.

This study was approved by the institutional ethics committee after review of the protocol and procedures employed (2018-0132-001). All study procedures complied with the principles of the 1946 Declaration of Helsinki, and its 2008 update.
